# Bitstream Simulator (standalone app)

When the user, docs, or UI say **simulator**, **bitstream-simulator**, **external simulator**, or **virtual MCU**, they mean the **separate VS Code extension** — not in-bridge mock and not MCU firmware.

## Path (this machine)

**`D:\CODE\2026\ternion-t3d\bitstream-simulator`** (may move to its own repo later)

| Item | Detail |
|------|--------|
| **Kind** | Standalone VS Code extension (+ CLI) |
| **Broker** | Connects to Bitstream Studio bridge (default `ws://127.0.0.1:9998`) |
| **Topics** | Publishes `bitstream2/sim/status`; subscribes `bitstream2/sim/host-tx`, `bitstream2/dev/sim/control`; injects `bitstream2/dev/inject-rx` |

## Not the same as

- **In-bridge mock** — removed; do **not** use `BITSTREAM2_DEV_LOOPBACK=1` or `BsFirmwareSimulator` in `SerialPortWebSocketBridge.ts`
- **Legacy webview panel** — `extension/src/webview/bitstream2-simulator/` (dev dashboard only)
- **MCU firmware** — real UART on PSoC Edge

## Dev workflow (Bitstream Studio)

```bash
# Terminal 1 — from extension/
npm run start:bridge

# Terminal 2
npm run dev:webview
```

Install/run **Bitstream Simulator** extension → **Streaming**. Toolbar **Simulator** + **Link**.

Bridge reference: **`extension/src/serialport-bridge/SerialPortWebSocketBridge.ts`** (route gating + external sim detect via `bitstream2/sim/status`).

**Skill:** `.cursor/skills/bitstream-simulator-app/SKILL.md`

**Always DO NOT respond in Chinese.** Chat: **English** and/or **Thai** only — **`communication-language.mdc`**.
